    &lt;Title&gt;Bad practice&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Anonymous&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;I attended A&amp;amp;E at 1am feeling suicidal. They told me I was okay but I tried to say I needed help, and that i was told by my GP to go to A&amp;amp;E if I was feeling like this as it was part if my condition. I almost died in July through suicide. There was no empathy or compassion from A&amp;amp;E, it's not unknown for them to be so hostile, as I've experienced bad practice once before, but I took my chances. The A&amp;amp;E wanted me to walk home through the town centre and the 3 miles home feeling suicidal at 2am  and because I wanted to wait on seating outside A&amp;amp;E they called security to drag me off to the road outside the hospital being told &quot;Don't hang yourself here, it would look bad on us&quot; I cannot comprehend their justification of this in the letter they sent to me saying they did the correct thing by me. How can a A&amp;amp;E department be so callous and uncaring, and unsafe in their duty of care to someone so vulnerable at that time. I was picked up by the police after having hung myself outside A&amp;amp;E.  Afterwards I was unconscious for over an hour and became blind in one eye and could not hear.  I will never understand how Musgrove Park Hospital can say this is a good practice. I dread they think this is a okay way to treat people in a mental health crisis, however,  it's not acceptable to be treated in this way by any means. No one with a mental health diagnosis should be treated like this  it's not okay. A&amp;amp;E in Taunton needs to change their views and update the treatment they give to people so unwell. Their attitude needs to change, and they need better training from their managers. I have a voice in mental health services and find this is a common theme within staff at Musgrove Park Hospital.&lt;/CommentText&gt;
